Description: A long episode of rain, at times heavy, is expected. A frontal system over the BC Coast will continue to give heavy rain to inland sections of the Central Coast tonight and Wednesday morning. Rainfall totals near 80 mm are possible by the time rain eases late Wednesday morning. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Wreckhouse Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds are expected or occurring. Maximum gusts: southeasterly up to 130 km/h today. Time span: continuing until this afternoon. Remarks: Winds will ease and shift to southwesterly this afternoon. ### Very strong winds may push your vehicle around especially on roads through mountain passes and along deep valleys. Wreckhouse wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 20 cm is expected. The snow will intensify tonight over the Chaleur Bay area and the tip of the Gaspé Peninsula, then on Wednesday over the Upper Gaspé area and the Lower North Shore. The snow will be accompanied by locally blowing snow. Conditions will improve Wednesday evening. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. A frontal system moved over the BC south coast today and gave heavy rain to the region. Rain will ease over most areas this evening but will continue over the central and eastern Fraser Valley through tonight. Total rainfall amounts of 40 to 60 mm are expected. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
